[2] Israel, positive environmental samples, locations
Date: Fri 12 Jul 2013
Source: Haaretz [edited]
http://www.haaretz.com/news/national/polio-virus-spreading-across-israel-via-sewer-systems.premium-1.535338


The poliovirus has continued to spread through sewer systems across Israel, based on widespread sample surveys of sewer systems recently ordered by the Health Ministry.

Still, no polio sufferers have been found, the Health Ministry said, stressing that the virus has been located in sewer systems only.

The survey found the virus in the Ayalon sewer system that handles sewage from the cities of Ramle, Lod and Modi'in and the communities located in the Gezer Regional Council; in the sewer system that handles sewage from the Lev Hasharon Regional Council, including the community of Kalansua; and in the sewage treatment plant that serves the communities of Jaljulia and Kafr Bara. The discovery of the poliovirus in these sewer systems follows the virus' discovery at sewage treatment plants serving Negev communities. The virus was 1st discovered in May [2013] in sewage from the Negev city of Rahat.

All the polioviruses found recently have a similar genetic structure to the strain of the virus found in December 2012 in Egypt, according to the director of Public Health Services in the Health Ministry, Prof. Itamar Grotto. According to Grotto, it is believed that the virus was brought to Israel by a carrier who was infected in Egypt, and has already been transmitted to additional people, although it is impossible to estimate the number of infected.

"It can be assumed that the virus has spread and infected people in the center of the country and the Sharon region," said Grotto. However, he added, it could not be ruled out that the virus was brought to the center of the country by people living in the south who work in the center.

The survey samples from sewer systems across the country have yet to find any polioviruses in Tel Aviv, Haifa, Jerusalem, Ashkelon or Eilat, or in the sewer systems of the central Dan region or of the north.

In recent days, the Health Ministry has increased preparations for a vaccination campaign that will provide an additional polio vaccine to children up to the age of 8 across the south. Currently children are vaccinated with an injection of a dead poliovirus at ages 2 months, 4 months, 6 months and one year, and then in the 2nd grade of school.

The new campaign would administer an additional polio vaccine that contains a weakened live virus in drop form to children up to age 8. Grotto said the final decision to carry out the vaccination campaign will be made based on the results of a fecal sample survey being conducted now by the Health Ministry in Negev communities.

World Health Organization figures show that the poliovirus is considered active in only 5 countries today. In Afghanistan, Pakistan and Nigeria the virus is considered to be "endemic"; in 1988, this description fit 125 countries. Isolated numbers of polio sufferers have also been found, according to the WHO, in Somalia and Kenya since the beginning of this year [2013].

Israel is likely to join these 2 countries should any individuals be diagnosed with polio. The WHO has a goal of eradicating polio worldwide by 2018.

To reduce the risk of contracting polio, the Health Ministry instructs individuals to be meticulous about personal hygiene, particularly washing hands after using the bathroom, before touching food and after changing infants' diapers. The ministry also called for parents to be meticulous about keeping up-to-date with routine vaccinations for their children up to age 6 at well-baby centers across the country.

[Byline: Dan Even]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[All of the new locales where WPV1 has been identified (Ramle, Lod and Modi'in and the communities located in the Gezer Regional Council, Lev Hasharon Regional Council, Jaljulia and Kafr Bara) are located in the Central District of Israel. The earlier report of WPV1 isolates were from environmental samples in the Negev District in the South of Israel (see prior ProMED-mail posts Poliomyelitis update (10): Israel, positive environmental samples, MOH 20130605.1756289, Poliomyelitis update (09): Israel, positive environmental samples, RFI 20130604.1754766, and Poliomyelitis update (08): Israel, environmental isolates, WHO, RFI 20130603.1753099 for more details).

The finding that the WPV1 isolates are similar genetically to those identified in Egypt in December 2012 (see Poliomyelitis - worldwide (01): Egypt ex Pakistan, Niger 20130122.1509210 for more details) is in keeping with continued circulation of the same virus as originally identified in May 2013 in Rahat and Beer Sheeba in the Southern District.

Israel is comprised of 6 main administrative districts: Jerusalem District, Northern District, Haifa District, Central District, Tel Aviv District, and the Southern District.

For more detailed information on the Central District of Israel, the Wikipedia entry provides links to information on the cities, local councils and regional councils http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_District_(Israel). -Mod.MPP]

******
[3] Israel, positive environmental samples
Date: Thu 11 Jul 2013
Source: Arutz Sheva [edited]
http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/169841#.UeAFeTvOuq9


Traces of the poliomyelitis virus are continuing to appear in sewage treatment facilities in southern and central Israel, according to the Health Ministry.

The virus, which can cause paralysis, was once considered eradicated. But nearly one million doses of the "live attenuated" oral vaccine were ordered at a cost of several million shekels after the live virus was 1st detected in February [2013] in routine samples of sewage extracted from Rahat.

Israel is one of only 5 countries in the world that routinely tests stool samples, via 16 sewage treatment plants around the country.

Health Minister Yael German stressed there is "no reason to panic," saying that not even one case of clinical poliomyelitis has appeared thus far.

But the ministry is continuing to monitor and examine stool samples around the country, and traces are continuing to spread. The areas where the virus has been detected include the Lev Hasharon area, Modi'in, Ramle, the Negev Bedouin city of Rahat, Be'er Sheva, Ashdod and Tel Aviv.

According to some experts who testified before the Knesset Health Committee last month [June 2013], some 10 percent of Negev residents have not been inoculated against the virus.

An advanced form of the oral polio vaccine is to be administered to some 150 000 children in the south this month, following last month's visit to Israel by officials from the World Health Organization and the US Centers for Disease Control.

Some rabbis in Jerusalem have begun to announce their recommendation to vaccinate all children under the age of 6.

A total of 5 vaccination stations were opened in Jerusalem for the purpose of distributing polio vaccines to the hareidi-religious population [ultra orthodox], which includes families who choose not to immunize their children at all.

In an alarming development, Knesset member Yisrael Eichler (UTJ) recently charged that many of the well-baby clinics in hareidi-religious neighborhoods around the country have failed to keep up with the high birthrate and to monitor the children's health in these families.

As a result, he warned, thousands of children in the country could be at risk.

[Byline: Hana Levi Julian]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The initial positive environmental samples were in sewage serving Arab communities in the Southern District with the speculation that there was introduction of the virus from a traveler to or from Egypt, where a similar WPV1 was identified in December 2012. Vaccination activities in the Southern District have been increased to raise coverages there and interrupt the apparent "silent" transmission of the WPV1 (in this case the use of the word "silent" means that there have not been clinical cases of polio associated with this circulating virus identified).

While the 2012 reported vaccination coverage with polio vaccine in Israel was 95 percent (according to data available on the WHO website: http://apps.who.int/immunization_monitoring/globalsummary/countries?countrycriteria%5Bcountry%5D%5B%5D=ISR), concern re: pockets of unvaccinated individuals where the WPV1 could circulate is valid. The above newswire highlights the concerns raised about sub-optimal vaccination coverages in the ultra-orthodox community in Jerusalem. In the past few years, there have been outbreaks of measles and mumps in the ultra-orthodox communities in Israel, the UK and the US (see prior ProMED-mail postings listed below), which serve as evidence of lower coverages with MMR vaccine (measles, mumps and rubella), and possibly suggestive of lower coverages with other vaccines, including the polio vaccine. (This moderator attempted to find information on vaccination coverage by vaccine and administrative division in Israel but was unsuccessful).

In addition to the environmental sampling for WPV1 in sewage, the Ministry of Health of Israel has begun doing stool sampling at mother and infant care centers and HMOs in the Southern District (http://www.health.gov.il/English/News_and_Events/Spokespersons_Messages/Pages/03072013_1.aspx). Results of this sampling will be available in several weeks. It will be interesting to know if WPV1 is detected from individuals, and to learn the vaccination status of the positive individuals. Israel uses the inactivated poliovirus vaccine (IPV) and one wonders if the circulation of the WPV1 is occurring in individuals with a history of 3 or more doses of IPV (see Duintjer Tebbens RJ, Pallansch MA, Chumakov KM, Halsey NA, Hovi T, Minor PD, Modlin JF, Patriarca PA, Sutter RW, Wright PF, Wassilak SG, Cochi SL, Kim JH, Thompson KM. Review and assessment of poliovirus immunity and transmission: synthesis of knowledge gaps and identification of research needs. Risk Anal. 2013 Apr;33(4):606-46. doi: 10.1111/risa.12031. Epub 28 Mar 2013). - Mod.MPP]

